    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-09-12T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-09-12T12:00:00-05:00" n="524"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d524">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 103.94/413</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SWG1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-09-12T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 12, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received September 13, 6.30 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5054. For <persName corresp="#p_BBM1">Baruch</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_SLL1">Summers</persName>:</p>
                <p>Further conferences indicate War Department are willing to submit programme to
                    Munitions Council and programme committees. Feel this will result in a scaling
                    down of the requirements for steel and explosives as these are so bitterly
                    criticised by both French and English representatives. There is increasing
                    evidence of necessity for scanning Allied requirements and ascertaining uses to
                    which allocation of steel is being put. We should also perfect the organization
                    of programme committees so there will follow the <pb facs="0699" n="607"
                        xml:id="pg_607"/> allocation of materials the Governments are producing. Am
                    arranging a permanent organization of War Industries Board in Paris-Have you
                    talked with <persName>Anderson?</persName> Would appreciate your
                    suggestions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sharp</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
